          <a:p>
            <a:r>
              <a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/>
              <a:t>Let me walk you through the six patterns that really matter for making agents more reliable. Step-level retry is the biggest one — right now if a tool times out, the entire turn fails. With retry policies, we can back off exponentially and try again. Each tool declares its own retry behavior, which is way better than one-size-fits-all. Observability gets way better too — right now you only see phase-level stuff like &quot;searching&quot; or &quot;thinking.&quot; We need tool-level detail. Dynamic memory refresh helps in long workflows — you don't want context from five minutes ago when something just changed. Parallel tool execution is already in there and it's a huge latency win when the LLM asks for multiple independent tools. CoT capture is about persistence — intermediate reasoning currently evaporates after each turn, but we should preserve it for the verifier and for debugging. And fallback chains make recovery smart — the coordinator can escalate to humans while the general agent retries simpler.</a:t>
            </a:r>
          </a:p>
        </p:txBody>
